<subSubSection id="48D355CA8FCDFE4348F752F3FCC4F9CE" pageId="387" pageNumber="388" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="007606418FCDFE4348F752F3FCC4F9CE" blockId="387.[150,1437,854,1598]" pageId="387" pageNumber="388">
<emphasis id="32BDDA538FCDFE4348F752F3FE9EFA07" bold="true" box="[199,315,1503,1527]" pageId="387" pageNumber="388">Remarks.</emphasis>
The Tanimbar Islands belong to the Australian zoogeographical region because they are located after the Wallace's line. However, 
<taxonomicName id="C7C97DC28FCDFE434A12512FFD31F9EB" box="[546,660,1539,1563]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Gonatopus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="387" pageNumber="388" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insulae">
<emphasis id="32BDDA538FCDFE434A12512FFD31F9EB" box="[546,660,1539,1563]" italics="true" pageId="387" pageNumber="388">G. insulae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is here treated, because of the continuity with the other Indonesian islands. The Wallace's line in fact is only a conventional border.
</paragraph>
